	<transcript sound="sound1"><![CDATA[So far, weâ€™ve talked about food contamination with pathogens, but it is also important to prevent food spoilage.<br /><br />Spoilage commences in food as soon as it is harvested, taken from the sea or slaughtered. Spoilage results from the action of bacteria, moulds, enzymes and yeasts.<br /><br />Poor hygiene practices, including poor temperature control, inadequate or unsuitable packaging and rough handling can result in damage and accelerate spoilage, as does pest infestation.<br /><br />Unlike food contaminated with pathogens, the effects of food spoilage can be seen, felt, tasted and smelt.<br /><br />Here are some common signs of spoilage:<li>Off odours;</li><li>Slime or stickiness;</li><li>Change in texture, for example dry or spongy;</li><li>Production of gas;</li><li>Discolouration;</li><li>Mould growth or whiskers;</li><li>Unusual taste, for example a sour taste; and</li><li>Blown cans or leaking packs.</li>]]></transcript>
	
		
